2026-04-13 15:46:32,087 INFO RLM iteration 2/50
Reasoning: We inspected the workbook and found it has a single sheet with three columns. Column B contains the source text strings; Column C is intended for the extracted 10‑character code. The instruction requires a formula that extracts a 10‑character sequence starting with "955" (which may be preceded by "/TES-") or "CHK", preferring the "955" sequence when both exist. A simple Excel formula using `SEARCH`, `MID`, and `IFERROR` can accomplish this:

```
=IFERROR(MID(B2, SEARCH("955", B2), 10), IFERROR(MID(B2, SEARCH("CHK", B2), 10), ""))
```

This tries to locate "955" first; if not found, it tries "CHK". If neither is found, it returns an empty string.  
We will write this formula into every cell of column C (starting from row 2) and save the modified workbook to the output directory, then set `output_spreadsheet` to that path.
Code:
```repl
import openpyxl
import os

# Paths
input_path = "/sandbox/input/input_spreadsheet/1_56920_init.xlsx"
output_dir = "/sandbox/output/output_spreadsheet"
os.makedirs(output_dir, exist_ok=True)
output_path = os.path.join(output_dir, "1_56920_init.xlsx")

# Load workbook (keep formulas)
wb = openpyxl.load_workbook(input_path, data_only=False)
ws = wb.active  # only one sheet

# Write formula into column C for all rows with data (skip header row)
formula_template = '=IFERROR(MID(B{row}, SEARCH("955", B{row}), 10), IFERROR(MID(B{row}, SEARCH("CHK", B{row}), 10), ""))'

for row in range(2, ws.max_row + 1):
    ws.cell(row=row, column=3).value = formula_template.format(row=row)

# Save to output location
wb.save(output_path)

# Set output variable
output_spreadsheet = output_path
print("Saved to", output_spreadsheet)
```
